<chapter xml:id="chapter-step" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Step functions</title>

<section xml:id="section-step-func">
<title>Concept</title>

<example xml:id="example-step-air-pump">
	<title>Inflating a raft</title>

	<p>
	You bring an inflatable raft on a trip to the lake,
	along with a portable air pump to inflate it.
	The air pump has three settings:

	<ul>

		<li>
			low
			(<quantity>
				<mag>0.25</mag>
				<unit base="metre" exp="3"/>
				<per  base="minute" />
			</quantity>)
		</li>

		<li>
			medium
			(<quantity>
				<mag>0.5</mag>
				<unit base="metre" exp="3"/>
				<per  base="minute" />
			</quantity>)
		</li>

		<li>
			high
			(<quantity>
				<mag>0.75</mag>
				<unit base="metre" exp="3"/>
				<per  base="minute" />
			</quantity>).
		</li>

	</ul>

	Notice that the specification for each of the three settings is given in <em>volume-per-unit-time</em>,
	so these are inflation <em>rates</em>.
	</p>

	<p>
	You run the pump at medium for one minute,
	but it's taking too long so you bump it up to high.
	After two minutes on high,
	the raft is nearly inflated but the pump seems like it's getting a bit hot as it works to counter-act the tendency of the raft to want to <em>deflate</em>,
	so you switch it to low for one more minute before turning it off.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-step-air-pump">
		<caption>Graph modelling output of an air pump with three settings.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-step-air-pump-graph" width="49.1%">
			<shortdescription>Graph modelling output of an air pump with three settings.</shortdescription>
			<!-- TODO description -->
			<latex-image><xi:include href="step.d/air-pump-graph.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

<p>
The model rate function graphed in <xref ref="figure-step-air-pump" />
is an example of a <term>step function</term>.
</p>

<definition xml:id="definition-step-function">
	<title>Step function</title>
	<statement><p> A function that <q>steps</q> between constant values on non-overlapping intervals. </p></statement>
</definition>

<p>
A function can only take on one output value at any given input value,
which is why we have an open circle at the endpoint of each line segment in the graph in <xref ref="figure-step-air-pump" />.
For example, if we call that inflation rate function <m>r</m>,
then <m>r(3) = 0.25</m> but <m>r(2.9999) = 0.75</m>.
Of course, this function is just a <term>model</term> of the behaviour of the air pump described in <xref ref="example-step-air-pump" /> <mdash />
we could have put open circles at the <em>beginnings</em> of the line segments and closed ones at the ends instead,
and it wouldn't affect our analysis of the inflation of the raft.
</p>

<p>
To describe a step function,
we use piecewise notation to specify the constant output values on different subdomains.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-step-piecewise">
	<title>Describing a step function</title>

	<p> Here is the graph of another step function. </p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-step-piecewise">
		<caption>An example step function.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-step-piecewise" width="67.6%">
			<shortdescription>Graph of an example step function.</shortdescription>
			<!-- TODO description -->
			<latex-image><xi:include href="step.d/piecewise.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

	<p>
	There is no <em>single</em> constant value or formula that describes the function's output values at every possible input value,
	so we describe the function's output values using different output values on different subdomains.
	<me>
		f(t) = \begin{cases}
			0 \amp t \lt 0 \\
			1 \amp 0 \le t \lt 1 \\
			2 \amp 1 \le t \lt 2 \\
			3 \amp 2 \le t \lt \pi \\
			\sqrt{2} \amp \pi \le t \lt 4.5 \\
			0 \amp t \ge 4.5
		\end{cases}
	</me>
	Suppose we wanted to determine the output value <m>f(\sqrt{3})</m> without the graph in front of us.
	We would first scan the subdomains in the right column,
	and notice that the input <m>t = \sqrt{3}</m> falls into the subdomain <m>1 \le t \lt 2</m>.
	Matching up this subdomain with its specified output value,
	we find that <m>f(\sqrt{3}) = 2</m>.
	</p>

</example>

<p> The simplest situation to deal with is a step function that <q>steps</q> at regular intervals. </p>

<definition xml:id="definition-step-regular-function">
	<title>Regular step function</title>
	<statement><p>
		A step function whose domain can be split into equal-length intervals
		so that the <q>steps</q> in output value only occur at boundaries between these intervals.
	</p></statement>
</definition>

<p>
The step function in <xref ref="example-step-piecewise" /> is not regular <mdash />
the steps in output value from <m>1</m> to <m>2</m> and from <m>2</m> to <m>3</m> both occur after intervals of length <m>1</m>,
but the next two steps in output value occur after intervals of length greater than <m>1</m>.
Because the irrational number <m>\pi</m> is involved in these longer two interval lengths,
there is no way to subdivide all these intervals into equal-length intervals so that output-value changes only occur at interval boundaries.
</p>

<p>
On the other hand,
the air pump model in <xref ref="example-step-air-pump" /> is regular because we can split the middle interval in half,
and then changes in output-value still only occur at boundaries of these length-<m>1</m> intervals.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-step-air-pump-regular">
	<caption>Graph modelling output of an air pump with three settings.</caption>
	<image xml:id="image-step-air-pump-regular-graph" width="49.1%">
		<shortdescription>Graph modelling output of an air pump with three settings.</shortdescription>
		<!-- TODO description -->
		<latex-image><xi:include href="step.d/air-pump-regular-graph.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

</section>

<section>
<title>Accumulation for a stepped rate function</title>

<subsection>
<title>Calculation pattern</title>

<p>
When a rate function is known to be constant,
computing accumulation is easy:
<me> \text{amount} = \text{rate} \times \text{duration} </me>.
When a quantity changes with a rate function that can be modelled by a step function,
then the rate function is not constant over its entire domain because it is not always the same rate value for all time.
However, a stepped rate function is constant over specific subdomains,
so we can still apply the above formula on each of those subdomains and then total up all of those partial accumulations.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-step-accumulation-air-pump">
	<title>Inflated raft</title>

	<p>
	For the situation described in <xref ref="example-step-air-pump" />,
	how much air has been pumped into the raft?
	To answer this question, we will split the inflation time period up.
	</p>

	<p>
	During the first minute when the pump is run on the medium setting,
	pumping air at a rate of
	<quantity>
		<mag>0.5</mag>
		<unit base="metre" exp="3"/>
		<per  base="minute" />
	</quantity>
	for one minute accumulates
	<me>
		(0.5 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 / \mathrm{min})
		\times
		(1 \unitsp \mathrm{min})
		=
		0.5 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3
	</me>
	of air in the raft.
	</p>

	<p>
	Over the next two minutes, when the air pump is on the high setting,
	we accumulate an additional
	<me>
		(0.75 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 / \mathrm{min})
		\times
		(2 \unitsp \mathrm{min})
		=
		1.5 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3
	</me>
	of air in the raft.
	</p>

	<p>
	Finally, over the final minute on the low setting,
	we accumulate an additional
	<me>
		(0.25 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 / \mathrm{min})
		\times
		(1 \unitsp \mathrm{min})
		=
		0.25 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3
	</me>
	of air in the raft.
	</p>

	<p>
	The total accumulation of air in the raft is the total of the calculations.
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\text{TOTAL} \amp =
			(0.5 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 / \mathrm{min})
			\times
			(1 \unitsp \mathrm{min})
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp \phantom{=} +
			(0.75 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 / \mathrm{min})
			\times
			(2 \unitsp \mathrm{min})
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp \phantom{=} +
			(0.25 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 / \mathrm{min})
			\times
			(1 \unitsp \mathrm{min})
		</mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = (0.5 + 1.5 + 0.25) \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = 2.25 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 </mrow>
	</md>.
	</p>

</example>

<p> Remember that we can have a rate function where the independent variable represents something other than time. </p>

<example xml:id="example-step-accumulation-saffron">
	<title>Accumulation of cost</title>

	<p>
	You are ordering a quantity of saffron, a very expensive spice, for your bulk food preparation business.
	The supplier offers a discount scheme based on the amount you order:
	<ul>
		<li> The first <quantity><mag>500</mag><unit base="gram"/></quantity> ordered is priced at $3.00 per gram. </li>
		<li>
		Any additional amount ordered <em>above</em> <quantity><mag>500</mag><unit base="gram"/></quantity> is priced at $2.75 per gram,
		for orders up to <quantity><mag>1</mag><unit base="gram" prefix="kilo"/></quantity> total.
		For example, if an order of <quantity><mag>600</mag><unit base="gram"/></quantity> is placed,
		then only the additional <quantity><mag>100</mag><unit base="gram"/></quantity> quantity is charged at $2.75 per gram,
		while the <q>initial</q> quantity of <quantity><mag>500</mag><unit base="gram"/></quantity> is still charged at $3.00 per gram.
		</li>
		<li> Any additional amount above <quantity><mag>1</mag><unit base="gram" prefix="kilo"/></quantity> is priced at $2.50 per gram. </li>
	</ul>
	</p>

	<p>
	The pricing model can be considered a rate function,
	where the inputs are in units of grams,
	and the outputs are in units of dollars-per-gram.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-step-saffron">
		<caption>Graph for a saffron pricing model.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-step-saffron-graph" width="56.7%">
			<shortdescription>Graph for a saffron pricing model.</shortdescription>
			<!-- TODO description -->
			<latex-image><xi:include href="step.d/saffron-graph.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

	<p>
	In this pricing model,
	the total <q>accumulated</q> cost of your order of
	<quantity><mag>1.2</mag><unit base="gram" prefix="kilo"/></quantity>
	is
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\text{COST} \amp =
			(3.00 \unitsp \$ / \mathrm{g})
			\times
			(500 \unitsp \mathrm{g})
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp \phantom{=} +
			(2.75 \unitsp \$ / \mathrm{g})
			\times
			(500 \unitsp \mathrm{g})
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp \phantom{=} +
			(2.50 \unitsp \$ / \mathrm{g})
			\times
			(200 \unitsp \mathrm{g})
		</mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \$ 1500 + \$ 1375 + \$ 500 </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \$ 3375 </mrow>
	</md>.
	</p>

</example>


</subsection>


<subsection>
<title>Geometric interpretation</title>

<p>
Consider what the calculations in <xref ref="example-step-accumulation-air-pump" /> represent on the graph of the inflation rate function.
On each subdomain, we used the constant-rate accumulation formula
<me> \text{amount} = \text{rate} \times \text{duration} </me>.
The rate represents the <em>height</em> of the graph on that particular subdomain,
while the duration represents the <em>length</em> of time that this rate was in effect.
Geometrically, the product of a <em>height</em> and a <em>length</em> represents the area of a rectangle:
<me> \text{area} = \text{height} \times \text{length} </me>.
So each partial accumulation calculation in <xref ref="example-step-accumulation-air-pump" />
corresponds to an area of a rectangle related to the graph of the stepped rate function.
Let's see exactly how.
</p>

<p>
First, suppose we actually turned the air pump off after the first minute of running on the medium setting.
The accumulation formula
<me>
	\text{air accumulation}
	=
	(0.5 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 / \mathrm{min})
	\times
	(1 \unitsp \mathrm{min})
</me>
corresponds to an area calculation for a rectangle of height <m>0.5</m> and length <m>1</m>.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-step-air-pump-1st-minute">
	<caption>Running the air pump on medium for one minute.</caption>
	<image xml:id="image-step-air-pump-graph-1st-min" width="49.1%">
		<shortdescription>Graph modelling output of an air pump for one minute.</shortdescription>
		<!-- TODO description -->
		<latex-image><xi:include href="step.d/air-pump-graph-1st-min.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<p>
Now let's take into account the additional two minutes running on high.
The accumulation formula
<me>
	\text{air accumulation}
	=
	(0.75 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 / \mathrm{min})
	\times
	(2 \unitsp \mathrm{min})
</me>
corresponds to an area calculation for a rectangle of height <m>0.75</m> and length <m>2</m>.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-step-air-pump-middle-minutes">
	<caption>Running the air pump on high for another two minutes.</caption>
	<image xml:id="image-step-air-pump-graph-middle-mins" width="49.1%">
		<shortdescription>Graph modelling output of an air pump for another two minutes.</shortdescription>
		<!-- TODO description -->
		<latex-image><xi:include href="step.d/air-pump-graph-middle-mins.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<p>
Finally, the accumulation formula
<me>
	\text{air accumulation}
	=
	(0.25 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 / \mathrm{min})
	\times
	(1 \unitsp \mathrm{min})
</me>
for the final minute running on low corresponds to an area calculation for a rectangle of height <m>0.25</m> and length <m>1</m>.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-step-air-pump-last-minute">
	<caption>Running the air pump on high for the final minute.</caption>
	<image xml:id="image-step-air-pump-graph-last-min" width="49.1%">
		<shortdescription>Graph modelling output of an air pump for another one minute.</shortdescription>
		<!-- TODO description -->
		<latex-image><xi:include href="step.d/air-pump-graph-last-min.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<p>
For the total accumulation, we added up the results of these three calculations.
Graphically,
<alert>the total accumulation corresponds to the total area of the rectangles formed between the stepped rate function's levels and the <m>t</m>-axis</alert>.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-step-air-pump-all">
	<caption>Total accumulation over the time period.</caption>
	<image xml:id="image-step-air-pump-graph-all" width="49.1%">
		<shortdescription>Graph modelling total accumulation pumped air.</shortdescription>
		<!-- TODO description -->
		<latex-image><xi:include href="step.d/air-pump-graph-all.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<warning>

	<p>
	We talk above about accumulation corresponding to <em>area</em>,
	but the results of each of our accumulation calculations in <xref ref="example-step-accumulation-air-pump" />
	are in units of <m>\mathrm{m}^3</m>, not <m>\mathrm{m}^2</m> <mdash />
	why is that?
	</p>

	<p>
	It is important to maintain a distinction between
	<ul>
		<li>
			the actual <em>physical quantity</em> whose accumulation we are determining
			(in <xref ref="example-step-accumulation-air-pump" />, this is a <em>volume</em> of air in units of <m>\mathrm{m}^3</m>)
		</li>
		<li>
			the <em>graphical area</em> formed by creating rectangles under the different levels of the step function.
		</li>
	</ul>
	We are making a graphical connection between the two product calculations
	<md alignment="gather">
		<mrow> \text{amount} = \text{rate} \times \text{duration} </mrow>
		<mrow> \text{area} = \text{height} \times \text{length} </mrow>
	</md>
	by interpreting each rate value as a <em>height</em> and each time duration as a <em>length</em> on the rate graph.
	Through this correspondence between the two formulas above,
	the <em>magnitudes</em> of accumulation and graphical area will be the same,
	but their units of measurement will not coincide.
	</p>

</warning>

<example xml:id="example-step-car-trip">

	<p>
	On a car trip from Camrose to Wetaskiwin,
	it takes the driver
	<quantity>
		<mag>6</mag>
		<unit base="minute"/>
	</quantity>
	at the posted Camrose city speed limit of
	<quantity>
		<mag>50</mag>
		<unit base="metre" prefix="kilo" />
		<per  base="hour" />
	</quantity>
	to get out onto the highway,
	then
	<quantity>
		<mag>24</mag>
		<unit base="minute"/>
	</quantity>
	at the posted highway speed limit of
	<quantity>
		<mag>100</mag>
		<unit base="metre" prefix="kilo" />
		<per  base="hour" />
	</quantity>
	to reach Wetaskiwin,
	and another
	<quantity>
		<mag>9</mag>
		<unit base="minute"/>
	</quantity>
	at the posted Wetaskiwin city speed limit of
	<quantity>
		<mag>50</mag>
		<unit base="metre" prefix="kilo" />
		<per  base="hour" />
	</quantity>
	to reach the final destination.
	</p>

	<p> With this model, our rate function is stepped. </p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-step-camrose-wetaskiwin">
		<caption>Graph of a rate-of-travel model.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-step-camrose-wetaskiwin" width="84.7%">
			<shortdescription>Graph of a rate-of-travel model.</shortdescription>
			<!-- TODO description -->
			<latex-image><xi:include href="step.d/camrose-wetaskiwin.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

	<p>(Note that minutes have been converted into hours for the graph.)</p>

	<p>
	Computing the total distance travelled is the same as calculating the total area of the three rectangles in <xref ref="figure-step-camrose-wetaskiwin" />:
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\text{TOTAL DISTANCE} \amp =
			(50 \unitsp \mathrm{km} / \mathrm{hr})
			\times
			(0.1 \unitsp \mathrm{hr})
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp \phantom{=} +
			(100 \unitsp \mathrm{km} / \mathrm{hr})
			\times
			(0.4 \unitsp \mathrm{hr})
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp \phantom{=} +
			(50 \unitsp \mathrm{km} / \mathrm{hr})
			\times
			(0.15 \unitsp \mathrm{hr})
		</mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = (5 + 40 + 7.5) \unitsp \mathrm{km} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = 52.5 \unitsp \mathrm{km} </mrow>
	</md>.
	</p>

</example>

<remark>

	<p>
	Keep in mind that the stepped rate function in <xref ref="example-step-car-trip" /> is a <em>simplified model</em>.
	In reality, a car cannot change its rate of travel instantaneously,
	and so our rate graph should have periods of increasing speed (that is, acceleration)
	and periods of decreasing speed (that is, deceleration).
	Moreover, it is unlikely the car was travelling at <em>exactly</em>
	<quantity>
		<mag>50</mag>
		<unit base="metre" prefix="kilo" />
		<per  base="hour" />
	</quantity>
	during the city portions of the trip,
	or at <em>exactly</em>
	<quantity>
		<mag>100</mag>
		<unit base="metre" prefix="kilo" />
		<per  base="hour" />
	</quantity>
	during the highway portion <mdash />
	in reality there would have been dips and rises in the rate graph,
	as the car went up or down hills, around corners,
	or was stuck behind or pulled out to pass slower-moving vehicles.
	However, often a <em>simplified</em> model is <em>good enough</em>,
	and trying to take into account all of the little variations in velocity during the trip might be too complicated for the simple purpose of estimating the distance travelled.
	</p>

	<p>
	In fact, we will learn in the next chapter how estimating accumulation using simplified models involving stepped rate functions can actually help us to calculate accumulation <em>exactly</em> for more complicated models.
	</p>

</remark>

<exercise>
	<title>Accumulation of cost</title>
	<p>
	In <xref ref="example-step-accumulation-saffron" />,
	we analyzed a purchasing scenario with a rate function describing variation in cost per unit <em>mass</em>,
	(whereas our other examples have all involved variation per unit <em>time</em>).
	Do you see how the total cost calculation in that example corresponds to a sum of areas of rectangles on the rate function graph?
	</p>
</exercise>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Oriented area</title>

<p> What if the rate is sometimes negative? </p>

<example xml:id="example-step-air-pump-with-leak">
	<title>Punctured raft</title>

	<p>
	One minute after inflating your raft
	(as in <xref ref="example-step-air-pump" />),
	a previously patched leak begins leaking again at a rate of
	<quantity>
		<mag>0.2</mag>
		<unit base="metre" exp="3"/>
		<per  base="minute" />
	</quantity>,
	and three minutes pass before you notice, quickly slap a piece of tape over the leak,
	and turn the air pump back on to medium for two minutes.
	(We'll assume in our <em>simplified</em> model that all of this happens instantaneously.)
	</p>

	<p>
	How much air is in the raft now?
	We just have to repeat the calculation of <xref ref="example-step-air-pump" />,
	but take into account the periods of air-loss and re-inflation.
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\text{TOTAL} \amp =
			(0.5 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 / \mathrm{min})
			\times
			(1 \unitsp \mathrm{min})
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp \phantom{=} +
			(0.75 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 / \mathrm{min})
			\times
			(2 \unitsp \mathrm{min})
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp \phantom{=} +
			(0.25 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 / \mathrm{min})
			\times
			(1 \unitsp \mathrm{min})
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp \phantom{=} -
			(0.2 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 / \mathrm{min})
			\times
			(3 \unitsp \mathrm{min})
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp \phantom{=} +
			(0.5 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 / \mathrm{min})
			\times
			(2 \unitsp \mathrm{min})
		</mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = (0.5 + 1.5 + 0.25 - 0.6 + 1) \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = 2.65 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 </mrow>
	</md>.
	</p>

</example>

<p>
Can we still interpret the calculation in <xref ref="example-step-air-pump-with-leak" />
as a sum of rectangle areas on the rate graph?
While leaking air, the amount of accumulated air in the raft is <em>decreasing</em>,
and so we should interpret the rate of air leakage as a <em>negative</em> rate of variance.
The static period between the initial inflation and the start of the leakage could also be interpreted as a period with rate
<quantity>
	<mag>0</mag>
	<unit base="metre" exp="3"/>
	<per  base="minute" />
</quantity>.
<md>
	<mrow>
		\text{TOTAL} \amp =
		(0.5 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 / \mathrm{min})
		\times
		(1 \unitsp \mathrm{min})
	</mrow>
	<mrow>
		\amp \phantom{=} +
		(0.75 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 / \mathrm{min})
		\times
		(2 \unitsp \mathrm{min})
	</mrow>
	<mrow>
		\amp \phantom{=} +
		(0.25 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 / \mathrm{min})
		\times
		(1 \unitsp \mathrm{min})
	</mrow>
	<mrow>
		\amp \phantom{=}
		{\color{red}
			+
			(0 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 / \mathrm{min})
			\times
			(1 \unitsp \mathrm{min})
		}
	</mrow>
	<mrow>
		\amp \phantom{=}
		{\color{red}
			+
			(-0.2 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 / \mathrm{min})
			\times
			(3 \unitsp \mathrm{min})
		}
	</mrow>
	<mrow>
		\amp \phantom{=} +
		(0.5 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 / \mathrm{min})
		\times
		(2 \unitsp \mathrm{min})
	</mrow>
	<mrow> \amp = \bigl( 0.5 + 1.5 + 0.25 + 0 + (-0.6) + 1 \bigr) \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 </mrow>
	<mrow> \amp = 2.65 \unitsp \mathrm{m}^3 </mrow>
</md>.
If we allow rectangles to be assigned <em>negative</em> area and also consider a line segment along the horizontal axis as a rectangle with height <m>0</m>,
then the above calculation is still a sum of rectangle areas.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-step-air-pump-leakage">
	<caption>Inflating and re-inflating an air raft.</caption>
	<image xml:id="image-step-air-pump-graph-leakage" width="81.7%">
		<shortdescription>Graph modelling inflating, partially deflating, and re-inflating an air raft.</shortdescription>
		<!-- TODO description -->
		<latex-image><xi:include href="step.d/air-pump-graph-leakage.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<definition xml:id="definition-step-positively-oriented-area">
	<title>Positively-oriented area</title>
	<statement><p>
		If a function is positive on a domain,
		then the area bounded between the graph of the function and the horizontal axis over that domain is <term>positively-oriented</term>
		and we assign positive number to that area.
	</p></statement>
</definition>

<figure xml:id="figure-step-positively-oriented">
	<caption>A positively-oriented area.</caption>
	<image xml:id="image-step-positively-oriented" width="45.5%">
		<shortdescription>A diagram of a positively-oriented area under the graph of a function.</shortdescription>
		<!-- TODO description -->
		<latex-image><xi:include href="step.d/positively-oriented.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<definition xml:id="definition-step-negatively-oriented-area">
	<title>Negatively-oriented area</title>
	<statement><p>
		If a function is negative on a domain,
		then the area bounded between the graph of the function and the horizontal axis over that domain is <term>negatively-oriented</term>
		and we assign a negative number to that area.
	</p></statement>
</definition>

<figure xml:id="figure-step-negatively-oriented">
	<caption>A negatively-oriented area.</caption>
	<image xml:id="image-step-negatively-oriented" width="45.5%">
		<shortdescription>A diagram of a negatively-oriented area under the graph of a function.</shortdescription>
		<!-- TODO description -->
		<latex-image><xi:include href="step.d/negatively-oriented.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>


</subsection>

</section>

<section>
<title>Sigma notation</title>

<subsection>
<title>Summing patterns</title>

<p>
In the examples in this section,
total accumulation was calculated as a sum of products.
The situation of calculating a sum where each term in the sum follows a pattern comes up a lot in mathematics,
so mathematicians have developed a special notation for it.
</p>

<assemblage>
<title>Sigma notation</title>

<p>
If we write <m>P(k)</m> to mean a calculation formula or pattern in the variable <m>k</m>,
then we can write
<me> \sum_{k = 1}^n P(k) </me>
to represent the sum
<me> P(1) + P(2) + P(3) + \dotsb + P(n) </me>.
The <term>Greek letter <m>\Sigma</m></term> stands for <q>Sum</q>,
the variable <m>k</m> is called the <term>index variable</term> for the sum,
and the <q>start</q> and <q>end</q> values <m>1</m> and <m>n</m> are called the <term>lower bound</term> and <term>upper bound</term>,
respectively,
for the summation.
</p>

</assemblage>

<note>
	<p>
	The Greek letter <m>\Sigma, \sigma</m> is called <q>sigma</q>,
	where <m>\Sigma</m> is the uppercase version and <m>\sigma</m> is the lower case version.
	This letter corresponds to the letter <em>S</em> in the English alphabet,
	hence its use to represent a <em>S</em>um.
	</p>
</note>

<example xml:id="example-step-sigma-squares">
	<title>Sum of squares</title>
	<p>
	Consider the <term>sum-of-squares</term> formula
	<me> 1 + 4 + 9 + 16 + 25 + 36 + 49 + 64 + 81 + 100 </me>.
	Recognizing each term in the sum as a square number,
	we can express each term as the result of the pattern
	<me> P(k) = k^2 </me>
	for increasing integer values of the variable <m>k</m>:
	<me> 1^2 + 2^2 + 3^2 + 4^2 + 5^2 + 6^2 + 7^2 + 8^2 + 9^2 + {10}^2 </me>.
	Based on this pattern, we can compactly express the above sum of squares using Sigma notation:
	<me> \sum_{k = 1}^{10} k^2 </me>.
	</p>
</example>

<p>
While we used the value <m>k = 1</m> as sort of a <q>default</q> start value in the definition of Sigma notation above,
we can use any start value we like, according to the summation pattern we are trying to describe.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-step-sigma-squares-higher-start">
	<title>Different starting value</title>
	<p>
	Here is another <term>sum-of-squares</term> formula:
	<me> 16 + 25 + 36 + 49 + 64 + 81 + 100 </me>.
	Since this summation pattern begins at the square of <m>4</m>,
	our Sigma-notation version of this sum is
	<me> \sum_{k = 4}^{10} k^2 </me>.
	</p>
</example>

<example xml:id="example-step-sigma-constant">
	<title>Summing a constant value</title>
	<p>
	Summing a constant value is, by definition, the same as multiplication
	(which is why we say <q>times</q>).
	<md>
		<mrow> \sum_{k = 1}^{6} 2 \amp = 2 + 2 + 2 + 2 + 2 + 2 </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = 6 \times 2 </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = 12 </mrow>
	</md>
	</p>
</example>

<p>
Take care when counting an indexed collection:
the number of objects is
<me> (\text{ending index value}) - (\text{starting index value}) + 1 </me>.
The <q><m>+ 1</m></q> is required because in the subtraction we have <q>taken away</q> every object up to and including the one indexed by the <q>starting index value,</q>
but we actually want to include that <q>starting</q> object in the collection being counted.
For example, if we have a sum indexed from <m>k = 1</m> to <m>k = n</m>,
then we are adding up <m>n</m> terms, not <m>n - 1</m> terms.
</p>

<identity xml:id="identity-step-sigma-constant">
	<title>Summing a constant value</title>
	<p>
	For a constant value <m>c</m> and integers <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> with <m>n \gt m</m>:
	<me> \sum_{k = m}^{n} c = (n - m + 1) \times c </me>.
	</p>
</identity>

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsection-step-sigma-properties">
<title>Properties of Sigma notation</title>

<p>
Keep in mind that calculating with Sigma notation is really just addition,
so every algebra rule for addition can be applied to Sigma notation.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-step-sigma-common-factor">
	<title>Sum of evens</title>
	<p>
	Suppose we want to sum a collection of even numbers:
	<me> 2 + 4 + 6 + 8 + 10 </me>.
	While there are variations of Sigma notation where the index variable may <q>step</q> by more than <m>1</m>,
	we can avoid that by expressing each of our even numbers as <m>2</m> times a number that increases by only <m>1</m> from term to term:
	<me> 2 \cdot 1 + 2 \cdot 2 + 2 \cdot 3 + 2 \cdot 4 + 2 \cdot 5 </me>.
	In Sigma notation, this sum can be expressed as
	<me> \sum_{k = 1}^{5} 2 k </me>.
	However, we also know that a common factor can be factored out of a sum:
	<me> 2 (1 + 2 + 3 + 4 + 5) </me>.
	This formula is <m>2</m> times a sum,
	so we can express it as <m>2</m> times a Sigma expression:
	<me> 2 \sum_{k = 1}^{5} k </me>.
	</p>
</example>

<identity xml:id="pattern-step-factoring-sigma">
	<title>Factoring in a Sigma expression</title>
	<p>
	For pattern <m>P(k)</m> and constant value <m>c</m>,
	<me> \sum_{k = 1}^n c P(k) = c \sum_{k = 1}^n P(k) </me>.
	</p>
</identity>

<warning><p>
	Only a <em>constant</em> may be factored out of Sigma notation <mdash />
	any expression involving the index variable <m>k</m> cannot be factored out,
	because if the sum were written out that variable part would be different from term to term and so would not actually be a <em>common</em> factor.
</p></warning>

<p>
As well as factoring out of sums, we also know that we may perform a series of additions in any order and with any groupings we wish.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-step-sigma-two-sums">
	<title>Summing two patterns</title>
	<p>
	Consider the sum
	<me> 2 + 6 + 12 + 20 + 30 + 42 + 56 + 72 + 90 + 110 </me>.
	It may not be obvious at first glance,
	but is the summation from <xref ref="example-step-sigma-squares" /> with each term increased by its index:
	<me> (1^2 + 1) + (2^2 + 2) + (3^2 + 3) + \dotsb + (10^2 + 10) </me>.
	In Sigma notation, this can be written
	<me> \sum_{k = 1}^{10} (k^2 + k) </me>.
	But we would come to the same result if we added all the squares first,
	and then added to that result the sum of the extra bits:
	<me> (1^2 + 2^2 + 3^2 + \dotsb + 10^2) + (1 + 2 + 3 + \dotsb + 10) </me>.
	We can write each of the bracketed Sigma expressions in Sigma notation separately:
	<me> \sum_{k = 1}^{10} k^2 + \sum_{k = 1}^{10} k </me>.
	</p>
</example>

<identity xml:id="pattern-step-summing-sum">
	<title>Summing separate patterns in a Sigma expression</title>
	<p>
	For patterns <m>P_1(k)</m> and <m>P_2(k)</m>,
	<me> \sum_{k = 1}^n \bigl( P_1(k) + P_2(k) \bigr) = \sum_{k = 1}^n P_1(k) + \sum_{k = 1}^n P_2(k) </me>.
	</p>
</identity>

<example xml:id="example-step-sigma-break">
	<title>Breaking up a sum</title>

	<p>
	Again consider the sum-of-squares pattern
	<me> 1 + 4 + 9 + 16 + 25 + 36 + 49 + 64 + 81 + 100 </me>.
	We can put brackets around any portions of the sum without changing the result:
	<me> (1 + 4 + 9 + 16 + 25 + 36) + (49 + 64 + 81 + 100) </me>.
	</p>

	<aside><title>BEDMAS</title><p>
		Remember what brackets mean in a mathematical formula:
		they are explicit instructions about the order in which the computations should proceed.
	</p></aside>

	<p>
	So this same sum that we expressed in <xref ref="example-step-sigma-squares" /> using a single Sigma expression
	can be re-expressed using two Sigma expressions, if we had some particular reason for wanting to do so:
	<me> \sum_{k = 1}^{6} k^2 + \sum_{k = 7}^{10} k^2 </me>.
	</p>

</example>

<identity xml:id="pattern-step-splitting-sigma">
	<title>Splitting up a Sigma sum</title>
	<p>
	If <m>q</m> is an index value between the starting index <m>m</m> and the ending index <m>n</m>,
	then
	<me> \sum_{k = m}^{n} P(k) = \sum_{k = m}^{q} P(k) + \sum_{k = q + 1}^{n} P(k) </me>.
	</p>
</identity>

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsection-step-sage">
<title>Summing in Sage</title>

<p>
Summation based on a pattern can be performed in Sage.
The syntax is below.
<cd><cline>
	sum(pattern, variable, start, end)
</cline></cd>
For example, the summation
<me> \sum_{k=1}^{5} 2 k + 1 </me>
becomes Sage input
<cd><cline>
	sum(2*k + 1, k, 1, 5)
</cline></cd>
However, remember that by default the only letter that Sage treats as a variable is <c>x</c>,
so if we want to use <c>k</c> for our index variable as we've been doing in our Sigma notation,
we have to first tell Sage that we want <c>k</c> to be treated as a variable.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-step-sage-sum">
	<title>Summing in Sage</title>

	<p> Let's try the example command above. </p>

	<sage>
		<input>
			var('k')
			sum(2*k + 1, k, 1, 5)
		</input>
		<output> 35 </output>
	</sage>

</example>

<exercise>
	<title>Try it yourself</title>
	<p>
	Use the blank Sage cell below to compute the sum
	<me> \sum_{k = 1}^{17} k^2 </me>.
	(If you've already evaluated the example Sage cell above,
	you won't need the <c>var('k')</c> command.)
	</p>
	<sage>
		<input></input>
		<output></output>
	</sage>
</exercise>

</subsection>

</section>

<section>
<title>Riemann sums</title>

<p>
When we sum up the (oriented) areas of rectangles formed by a step function,
the sum is called a <term>Riemann sum</term>.
</p>

<biographical>
	<title>Georg Friedrich Bernhard Riemann</title>
	<p>1826 <ndash /> 1866.</p>
</biographical>

<definition xml:id="definition-step-riemann">
	<title>Riemann sum</title>
	<statement><p>
		Suppose <m>s(t)</m> is a step function that takes on values
		<me>
			s(t) = \begin{cases}
				h_1 \amp t_0 \le t \lt t_1 \\
				h_2 \amp t_1 \le t \lt t_2 \\
				h_3 \amp t_2 \le t \lt t_3 \\
				\amp \vdots \\
				h_n \amp t_{n - 1} \le t \lt t_n
			\end{cases}
		</me>.
		If we write <m>\change{t_k}</m> to represent the length of the subdomain <m>t_{k - 1} \le t \lt t_k</m> so that
		<me> \change{t_k} = t_k - t_{k - 1} </me>,
		then the sum of (oriented) rectangle areas
		<me> \sum_{k = 1}^{n} h_k \change{t_k} </me>
		is called the <term>Riemann sum</term> for <m>s(t)</m> over the domain <m>t_0 \le t \le t_n</m>.
	</p></statement>
</definition>

<example xml:id="example-step-riemann-air-pump">
	<title>Riemann sum for the air pump</title>

	<p>
	Let's unpack the notation of the definition above for the <em>inflate-deflate-reinflate</em> model
	from <xref ref="example-step-air-pump-with-leak" />.
	The step function in the model <q>steps</q> output values at the following input values.
	<md>
		<mrow> t_0 \amp = 0 \amp t_2 \amp = 3 \amp t_4 \amp = 5 \amp t_6 \amp = 10 </mrow>
		<mrow> t_1 \amp = 1 \amp t_3 \amp = 4 \amp t_5 \amp = 8 </mrow>
	</md>
	The corresponding output height values between these stepping input values are:
	<md>
		<mrow> h_1 \amp = 0.5  \amp h_3 \amp = 0.25 \amp h_5 \amp = -0.2 </mrow>
		<mrow> h_2 \amp = 0.75 \amp h_4 \amp = 0    \amp h_6 \amp = 0.5  </mrow>
	</md>.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-step-air-pump-leakage-riemann">
		<caption>Riemann sum parameters for inflating and re-inflating an air raft.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-step-air-pump-graph-leakage-riemann" width="100%">
			<shortdescription>Graph modelling inflating, partially deflating, and re-inflating an air raft.</shortdescription>
			<!-- TODO description -->
			<latex-image><xi:include href="step.d/air-pump-graph-leakage-riemann.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

	<p>
	The subdomain lengths are as follows.
	<md>
		<mrow> \change{t_1} \amp = t_1 - t_0 = 1 </mrow>
		<mrow> \change{t_2} \amp = t_2 - t_1 = 2 </mrow>
		<mrow> \change{t_3} \amp = t_3 - t_2 = 1 </mrow>
		<mrow> \change{t_4} \amp = t_4 - t_3 = 1 </mrow>
		<mrow> \change{t_5} \amp = t_5 - t_4 = 3 </mrow>
		<mrow> \change{t_6} \amp = t_6 - t_5 = 2 </mrow>
	</md>
	Then our Riemann sum is
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\sum_{k = 1}^{6} h_k \change{t_k}
			\amp = h_1 \change{t_1} + h_2 \change{t_2} + h_3 \change{t_3} + h_4 \change{t_4} + h_5 \change{t_5} + h_6 \change{t_6}
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp = 0.5 \cdot 1 + 0.75 \cdot 2 + 0.25 \cdot 1 + 0 \cdot 1 + (-0.2) \cdot 3 + 0.5 \cdot 2
		</mrow>
	</md>,
	just as in our previous calculation,
	and each term in the sum represents an oriented rectangle area,
	as pictured in <xref ref="figure-step-air-pump-leakage" />
	(though one of the rectangles has height <m>0</m> and can't be seen in that diagram).
	</p>

</example>

<identity xml:id="pattern-step-regular-riemann">
	<title>Riemann sum for a regular step function</title>

	<p>
	For a regular step function, we can split the domain into subdomains of equal length,
	so that <m>\change{t_k}</m> is the same value for each subdomain.
	</p>

	<p>
	Writing <m>\change{t}</m> for this common subdomain length,
	if the original domain is <m>a \le t \le b</m>
	then the length of each subdomain should be
	<me> \change{t} = \frac{b - a}{n} </me>,
	where <m>n</m> is the number of subdomains.
	</p>

	<p>
	Furthermore, we can factor this common length out of our sum,
	so that
	<me>
		\sum_{k = 1}^{n} h_k \change{t_k}
		= \sum_{k = 1}^{n} h_k \change{t}
		= \left(\sum_{k = 1}^{n} h_k\right) \change{t}
		= \left(\sum_{k = 1}^{n} h_k\right) \left( \frac{b - a}{n} \right)
	</me>.
	</p>
</identity>

<example xml:id="example-step-regular-riemann-air-pump">
	<title>Riemann sum for the air pump using a regular step function</title>

	<p> Let's redo <xref ref="example-step-riemann-air-pump" /> but interpreting the rate function as a regular step function. </p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-step-air-pump-leakage-regular-riemann">
		<caption>Regular Riemann sum parameters for inflating and re-inflating an air raft.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-step-air-pump-graph-leakage-regular-riemann" width="100%">
			<shortdescription>Graph modelling inflating, partially deflating, and re-inflating an air raft.</shortdescription>
			<!-- TODO description -->
			<latex-image><xi:include href="step.d/air-pump-graph-leakage-regular-riemann.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

	<p>
	We have more subdomains this time,
	because we have split the longer subdomains up so that each subdomain has the same length.
	</p>

	<p>
	Factoring out the common subdomain length,
	we have
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\sum_{k = 1}^{10} h_k \change{t}
			\amp = \left(\sum_{k = 1}^{10} h_k\right) \change{t}
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp = (h_1 + h_2 + h_3 + h_4 + h_5 + h_6 + h_7 + h_8 + h_9 + h_{10}) \change{t}
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp = (0.5 + 0.75 + 0.75 + 0.25 + 0 + (-0.2) + (-0.2) + (-0.2) + 0.5 + 0.5) \cdot 1
		</mrow>
	</md>.
	This Riemann sum corresponds to the net (oriented) area of ten rectangles
	(though again one of the rectangles has height <m>0</m> and can't be seen).
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-step-air-pump-regular-leakage">
		<caption>Inflating and re-inflating an air raft.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-step-air-pump-graph-regular-leakage" width="81.7%">
			<shortdescription>Graph modelling inflating, partially deflating, and re-inflating an air raft.</shortdescription>
			<!-- TODO description -->
			<latex-image><xi:include href="step.d/air-pump-graph-regular-leakage.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

<remark><p>
	It may seem that summing ten rectangle areas in <xref ref="example-step-regular-riemann-air-pump" />
	is more work than summing six rectangle areas in <xref ref="example-step-riemann-air-pump" />.
	But when programming a computer to do such sums,
	the regularly-spaced ten rectangles is easier to program then the irregularly-spaced six rectangles,
	and computers don't care how many rectangle areas you ask them to sum
	(unless the number of rectangles is very, very large).
</p></remark>

</section>


<!-- <xi:include href="./step.d/activities.ptx" />
<xi:include href="./step.d/exercises.ptx" /> -->

</chapter>
